## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

Your code has four patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Prevents rethrow so `finally` runs | Remove — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |
| **Thread.Abort()** | `Stop()` force-kills thread | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime will **not** terminate your worker thread. Your `Stop()` method will hang forever if `GetNextItem()` blocks.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — mirrors the old ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed: OperationCanceledException doesn't auto-rethrow.
                // The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null || _workerThread == null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Abort as fallback
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop — log a warning. You cannot force-kill it.
            // If this happens, GetNextItem/ProcessItem aren't honoring the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### Critical: You must also update `GetNextItem`

The old code comments that `GetNextItem()` "may block." If it blocks indefinitely, cancellation **will never take effect** — cooperative cancellation only works if the blocking call checks the token.

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, ignores cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — unblocks when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}

// If using Thread.Sleep to poll:
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);
// AFTER
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000); // wakes immediately on cancel
```

---

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing the token to `GetNextItem`** | The thread stays blocked forever — `Stop()` hangs. This is the #1 migration failure. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** | Let it propagate except at the top-level loop. The `when` filter above ensures you only catch your own cancellation. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` does long work, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside it at regular intervals. |
| **Replacing `Thread.Abort` with `Thread.Interrupt`** | Also obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9). Use `CancellationToken` consistently. |

### Key Paradigm Shift

**.NET Framework:** The runtime *injects* `ThreadAbortException` into the thread — the thread doesn't need to cooperate.

**.NET 8:** The thread must *voluntarily* check `CancellationToken` — if it doesn't check, it won't stop. Every blocking call in the chain (`GetNextItem`, `ProcessItem`, I/O operations) must accept and forward the token.
